<subSubSection id="3639B98029E1B4D53CA6E2DC1191C985" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="E603DAE550F2E97A27AF07014F3A1945" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="20A78246973DB0C80B0C3676CB03240F" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
Native to the Palaearctic region. Widespread in Europe, also recorded from North Africa and Caucasus (
<bibRefCitation id="F29001D53AB2B8A8B1D4EC7E7E2C485D" author="Daffner, H" journalOrPublisher="Folia Entomologica Hungarica" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="9 - 163" refId="B41" refString="Daffner, H, 1983. Revision der palaearktischen Arten der Tribus Leiodini Leach (Coleoptera, Leiodidae). Folia Entomologica Hungarica 44: 9 - 163" title="Revision der palaearktischen Arten der Tribus Leiodini Leach (Coleoptera, Leiodidae)." volume="44" year="1983">Daffner 1983</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="538A8D97A02B24AB6E06D179E0252A01" author="Perreau, M" editor="Loebl, I" journalOrPublisher="Canadian Journal of Arthropod Identification" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" refId="B169" refString="Perreau, M, Loebl, I, Smetana, A, 2004. Leiodidae. In: LoeblISmetanaA (Eds) Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera (Vol.2). Apollo Books, Stenstrup, 133-203." title="Leiodidae. In: LoeblISmetanaA (Eds) Catalogue of Palaearctic Coleoptera (Vol. 2). Apollo Books, Stenstrup, 133 - 203." year="2004">Perreau 2004</bibRefCitation>
). Adventive in the Nearctic region (Ontario, Canada).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C61D8AEC8D7504A869E5D23574EE2601" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="canadian records">
<paragraph id="4A8BA9C031BB6533FF14B1E4066A5D16" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Canadian records.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F5EAA760C246482EB186C3BE6549054C" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Ontario: Puslinch Township, 15-Aug-2010 to 22-Aug-2010 (1 ex, CBG); Guelph, 18-Aug-2010 (1 ex, CBG).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="5323E72968F299F0559F49AFB9829D48" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="diagnostic information">
<paragraph id="F0BBA174E0D685CCBA1B8D99BD798E2D" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Diagnostic information</paragraph>
<paragraph id="23B2458164E062F9E79D2AFEBA42C332" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
(based on 
<bibRefCitation id="14E2CF49838DD113A8F62727BEACC056" author="Daffner, H" journalOrPublisher="Folia Entomologica Hungarica" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="9 - 163" refId="B41" refString="Daffner, H, 1983. Revision der palaearktischen Arten der Tribus Leiodini Leach (Coleoptera, Leiodidae). Folia Entomologica Hungarica 44: 9 - 163" title="Revision der palaearktischen Arten der Tribus Leiodini Leach (Coleoptera, Leiodidae)." volume="44" year="1983">Daffner 1983</bibRefCitation>
). Body length 2.2-4 mm. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation id="2F3262C28E6AA1087D1E44AF1A1270AE" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Leiodes polita (Marsham) A habitus L. Borowiec B male left metafemur, dorsal view C aedeagus, ventral view D aedeagus, lateral view. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (A), 0.5 mm (B), 0.2 mm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362138" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figure2">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
. Red-brown or yellow-brown, head, pronotum and the sutural and lateral margins of elytra sometimes darkened. Antennae long, with a strongly transverse, darkened club, last antennomere narrower than antennomere 10. Head normally with four punctures in transverse series. Basal margin of pronotum sinuate laterally. Mesoventrite with a long, low and evenly curved medial carina, not reaching the transverse carina and without excavation anteriorly. Metaventrite approximately as long as abdominal ventrites 1 and 2 combined. Elytra with regular, strongly and densely punctate striae, interstitial punctures sparse. Elytra not transversely strigose or strongly microsculptured. Elytral stria 9 separated from side margin at basal third, forming a subhumeral row of punctures. Protibiae only moderately widened towards apex. Metafemora in both sexes with an apical projection at both inner and outer margins, projections stronger in males (
<figureCitation id="811EF03306E8F9F0E0C519EC15D72C46" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Leiodes polita (Marsham) A habitus L. Borowiec B male left metafemur, dorsal view C aedeagus, ventral view D aedeagus, lateral view. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (A), 0.5 mm (B), 0.2 mm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362138" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figure2">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
). Male metatibiae bent inward starting from the basal third. Male genitalia as in 
<figureCitation id="7A2E416754E8B01ECF3694F35AD40EEE" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Leiodes polita (Marsham) A habitus L. Borowiec B male left metafemur, dorsal view C aedeagus, ventral view D aedeagus, lateral view. Scale bars: 1.0 mm (A), 0.5 mm (B), 0.2 mm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362138" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.894.37862.figure2">Fig. 2C, D</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CE2859E48BCCF4F1CA469DC5403B1DF3" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="bionomic notes">
<paragraph id="F56D1EE9EF263FF24EBAB985E15B7732" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Bionomic notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9BAA299B69F1349CC233E7393391CA7D" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
This eurytopic species is found in forests, forest edges, heaths, gardens etc. in Europe (
<bibRefCitation id="87FC4CD7E4FD384251D0A36FC6AC9B14" author="Koch, K" journalOrPublisher="Goecke &amp; Evers Verlag, Krefeld" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" refId="B115" refString="Koch, K, 1989b. Die Kaefer Mitteleuropas, Oekologie (Vol. 2). Goecke &amp; Evers Verlag, Krefeld" title="Die Kaefer Mitteleuropas, Oekologie (Vol. 2)." year="1989 b">Koch 1989b</bibRefCitation>
). The Canadian specimens were collected with Malaise traps in suburban residential areas in southern Ontario.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2155CFA2847DB4CCFA7A59EE2488A696" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="comments">
<paragraph id="835CD5FE6E032FBDA1AB32970C26851B" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="ED5FF0E2F8B2992C7AB15F3A1AF981EF" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
<taxonomicName id="3FABBC397399CC8E93CCD59E65B7184B" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Leiodes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Leiodes polita" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="polita">
<emphasis id="027FB4FC725986B1294DD328B1C45F22" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Leiodes polita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
leads to 
<taxonomicName id="21CB8ADF68E6F78E5D06FFC4B56A315F" genus="L." lsidName="L. quebecensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="quebecensis">
<emphasis id="46FB496E383A3FD82821AA7AB6AE5C98" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">L. quebecensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Baranowski, 1993 in the key to North American species of 
<taxonomicName id="82716374983C9E1135E07A94B1AB73FB" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Leiodes" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Leiodes" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="AA0C22C97BF76AF0662A15B31DFE11E4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Leiodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="9471CF00BADC5CB49C31DD2DD2E0DFFA" author="Baranowski, R" journalOrPublisher="Entomologica Scandinavica Supplementum" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="1 - 149" refId="B15" refString="Baranowski, R, 1993. Revision of the genus Leiodes Latreille of North and Central America. Entomologica Scandinavica Supplementum 41: 1 - 149" title="Revision of the genus Leiodes Latreille of North and Central America." volume="41" year="1993">Baranowski 1993</bibRefCitation>
). It can be distinguished by the sinuate basal margin of the pronotum (straight in 
<taxonomicName id="BE2D88BB60D56BCAF8566ADBD6D562CD" genus="L." lsidName="L. quebecensis" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="quebecensis">
<emphasis id="19C0C9E33B3CE8255D3C234B85663475" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">L. quebecensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and related species), differently formed projections of the metafemora, and the male genitalia.
</paragraph>
